===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{recons|patten|lang=enm}}, alteration (with loss of medial ''l'') of {{etyl|enm}} {{term|platten|lang=enm}}, {{term|pletten||to pat|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|plættan||to buffet, strike, slap, smack, to give a sounding blow|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|plat-|to strike, beat|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|b(e)lad-||b(e)led-|to strike, beat|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|dum|-}} {{term|platten|lang=dum}}, {{term|pletten||to strike, bruise, crush, rub|lang=dum}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|platzen||to split, burst, break up|lang=de}}, {{etyl|bar|-}} {{term|patzen||to pat|lang=bar}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|plätta|lang=sv}}, {{term|pjätta||to pat, tap|lang=sv}}. For loss of ''l'', compare {{term|patch}} for {{term|platch}}; {{term|pate}} for {{term|plate}}, etc. See {{l|en|plat}}.

